content.description: Lots of stacked rocks and choss.  Climbing this will produce lots of smaller rocks, hence the name.  Highly recommended that belayer stays behind cover for safety.
content.location: Starts at the toe of the north wall.  Make your way up the obvious shatter/crack system, staying right as needed.  Stable anchor options.

content.description: Stem up the opening and carefully place gear as you go.  Crumbly.  Follow the crack system on the right up through a fun chimney.  Reliable anchor can be built at the top, benefits from a long extension.
content.location: Starts at the obvious incut portion that splits the north Doubletree Wall.

content.description: Short, loose, and frankly dangerous.  All protection is questionable.  But it will get you to the mini-tower.  Simple walk-off on back side.
content.location: Right side of the north Doubletree Wall.  Starts just right of the dark fissure.  Funky crack system leads to the miniature rock tower.

content.description: Route begins on a black flake and moves up into a slight book feature.  At the first major flake, abandon the crack and swing out right on the exposed face for great holds.  Continue up another large, fragile flake with a crumbly top hand rail.  Finish on a ramp with poor protection and touch the glorious roots of the Doubletree.  Doubletree makes an acceptable belay anchor, but might not make a good toprope/rappel anchor.
content.protection: Lots of finger gear and a single #3 cam
content.location: Located on the north wall leading up to the Double Trees.  This is the left route located close to the murder cave.
